    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.21.4-8_0001" />
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial"><unclear>4</unclear></fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline><note type="curatorial">June 6, 1944</note></dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt;</salute>
                    <note type="curatorial">[Chicago, Ill.]</note>
                </opener>
                <p>I had felt beforehand that all of your audience would thoroughly enjoy hearing you. But the enjoyment was away beyond my anticipation, because I did not dream you would be so generous as to read that splendid play.</p>
                
                <p>When I invited you to be present, I did not dare to be so presumptuous as to expect much more than a lyric or two.</p>
                
                <p>It was most gracious
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.21.4-8_0002"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">5</fw>
                
                    of you and a hight compliment to the intelligence of our Society.</p>
                
                <p>I am sure there can be no doubt in your mind as to your receptive audience.</p>
                
                <p>I have had three calls asking me where they can hear you again and two asking me if I know what you charge for a programme.</p>
                
                <p>I said I would ask if your folders are out for the coming season.</p>
                
                <p>I am going to contact the Drama League,
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.21.4-8_0003"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">6</fw>
                
                    some of whose members are very good friends of mine.</p>
                
                <p>I think your dramatic play would be a fine vehicle for one of their programme days.</p>
                
                <p>I will also contact <unclear>Mundelein</unclear> College for Girls, and Rosary College of River Forest.</p>
                
                <p>Both of these have out-standing speakers every year.</p>
                
                <p>The William Vaughan Moody Foundation of the University of Chicago is another probable field for you.</p>
                
                <p>They had Frost this season,
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.21.4-8_0004"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">7</fw>
                
                    and Hinsdale had him two years ago.</p>
                
                <p>I want to tell you what one of our guests from a prominent South Side Club said on the telephone yesterday. I quote:&#8212; "I have heard all the prominent and great actors of my time,&#8212;never have I heard delivery or diction that surpassed Dr. Neihardt's or even compared with his. I think his dramatic play a masterpiece".</p>
                
                <p>Should you wish her signed statement I feel confident she would give it.</p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.21.4-8_0005"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">8</fw>
                
                <p>The Chicago Branch of the Catholic Poetry Society of America extends to you its deep gratitude for your splendid reading of your dramatic play, last night. I can frankly say, it is the finest play and the best poetry rendition we have ever listened to.</p>
                
                <p>Our deep appreciation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Cordially</salute> 
                    <signed><unclear>Con E. Morow</unclear></signed>
                
                June 6- 1944.
                Mrs M.G. Morow
                Board of Directors
                C.P.S.
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
